What’s the Trump’s Tweets Association?

Unsupervised Learning Primier: Association Rule Mining

Abstract

This article“s goal is to explore the possibilities of unsupervised learning methods in Data Science. I am currently enrolled in the 1st semester of CEE”s Best Data Science Programme, MSc in Data Science at the University of Warsaw. By this time, I can tell, that association rule mining is fundamental to acquire if you wish to have a successful career in Data Science or Machine Learning.

These methods are often connected to transaction analytics. We look for the relations between items. It works similar to correlation, but the items we purchase are categorical values, not integers or floats, that is why we use association rules, which you can think of like the correlation between sets. But, the universe of use cases we can apply this method is far broader than our grocery baskets. We can use it for images, or sentences. We can treat sentences like baskets or transactions with multiple items inside. An author decides upon which words to use, just like we decide what to put to our grocery basket.

Here, I will use Twitter Data, regarding Donald Trump“s Tweets, which can be found on Kaggle Datasets. I will explore the association between words and sentiment inside the short texts. Twitter helps here a lot because Tweets have a character limit and often consists of several words, to transport the message.

Happy Reading!

Based on documentation provided by Kaggle User, and this simple summary, we can differentiate 11 columns in this dataset of 7375 unique records:

  • Date: Datestamp of each Tweet in YY-MM-DD format,

  • Time: Timestamp of each Tweet in HH-MM-SS format,

  • Tweet_Text: The actual text content of each Tweet,

  • Type: an indication, whether the Tweet was pure text, or text related to the link (“text”/“link”),

  • Media_Type: an indication, whether the Tweet was pure text, or text related to the photo (“null”/“photo”),

  • Hashtags: any written hashtags in the Tweet,

  • Tweet_Id: unique value for each Tweet,

  • Tweet_Url: unique link to each Tweet,

  • twt_favourites_IS_THIS_LIKE_QUESTION_MARK: number of favourites, that are assigned to certain Tweet,

  • Retweets: number of retweets, that are assigned to certain Tweet,

  • X and X.1 columns that do not have documentation.

For the purpose of this research project, I will use only a part of accessible columns and characteristics of each Tweet. Moreover, I will make use only of a portion of the Tweets. I would like to get rid of any Tweets with external context, meaning those with Hashtags, Links and Photos will be dropped, as they may refer directly to different source or event.

Now, we need to firsly, get rid of the misleading characters like \n, which was typed in text to indicate hard enter, and extract individual words from the Tweets. Also, we will make sure, that stopwords are deleted (however, I am living stopwords like “we”, given that these are Tweets from the middle of a Presidential Campaing, and this can matter in the analysis). (Un)fortunately, we ended up with a list of lists, that need to be unpacked and rewritten into the matrix.

sample(stopwords, 5)
## [1] "can"   "few"   "on"    "yours" "how"
cleanLink = function(x) gsub("\n", " ", x)
cleanStopwords = function(x) gsub(stopwords, "", x)
stringSep = function(x) str_split(x, " ")

dataText = dataText %>%
  apply(2, cleanLink)

dataText = dataText %>%
  apply(2, cleanStopwords)
## Warning in gsub(stopwords, "", x): argument 'pattern' ma długość > 1 i
## tylko pierwszy element zostanie użyty
dataSeparated = apply(dataText, 2, stringSep)

dataBasket = matrix(nrow = lengths(dataSeparated[1]),
                    ncol = max(lengths(dataSeparated[[1]]))
                    )

for(i in 1:lengths(dataSeparated)){
  for(j in 1:lengths(dataSeparated[[1]][i])){
    dataBasket[i,j] = dataSeparated[[1]][[i]][j]
  }
}

dataBasketSmall = dataBasket[1:250,]

write.csv2(dataBasketSmall, "dataBasketSmall.csv")

After a quick clean of artificial columnNames, Index value, as well as deleting links, “@Username” values and punctuation marks, we can load our “Transaction Data”. It could have beed done in R, by replacing values, that meet certain requirements, but Excel was faster and I could review the data once more. And the data processing part is not the core of this analysis. One can write many Primiers on dealing with strings, webscraping text datasets and applying regular expressions to clearing.

During the creation of this project I encountered a certain pecularity, which is connected to analyzing natural language using association rules (or market basket analysis).

Tweets are substantially more heterogeneuous that baskets of products. When at first, I ran the algorithms without deleting the stopwords, the rules were working great, but the analysis lost its sense, as most of the rules were just the English stopwords like “in”, “at”, “the”, etc.

When I decided, to remove stopwords, the sample of N Tweets, was too heterogeneous to create any relevant rules. In other words, when we extract only the nouns and verbs, without stopwords, Tweets are becoming too different from each other.

Below is the example of very short, homogeneous subset of tweets, and in parallel I show the analysis of the bigger subset, but with stopwords included

Key Measures

Before moving into the next parts of the analysis, let me introduce our key measures, that are the core of the Association Rule Mining. As you can see, I am not explaining it in generic manner, but adjusted to our dataset. I am sure you can find a lot of documentation on the web as well.

  • Support: Ratio between (Number of Tweets with word X and word Y) and (Total number of Tweets)

  • Confidence: Ratio between (Number of Tweets with word X and word Y) and (Total number of Tweets with word X)

  • Expected Confidence: Ratio between (Number of Tweets with word Y) and (Total number of Tweets)

  • Lift: Ratio between Confidence and Expected Confidence

Now, I will create rules. They explain occurence of certain variables with different one in Tweets (transactions). As I have a lot of words (items) in Tweets (transactions), I will set the support measurement to the 15% for the smaller subset and 10% for the bigger (with stopwords included), which will filter the data more. I am also setting the maximum lenght, in order to prevent the algorithm from creating too long rules.

By sorting those rules using the lift, we see, which rules occured the most (0.13 support mean that in 13% of all Tweets in the sample). Moreover, the confidence sorting enables us to see, which items occur the most often with one another, and last but not least, we may also take a look at the lift. Let“s see, which words are associated with the word”Hillary“. The lhs and rhs can be replaced, but then we may obtain empty baskets, hence let me stick with the convention below.

tweetsHillary = apriori(Tweets_2, parameter = list(supp = .01, confidence = .01),
                       appearance = list(default = "lhs", rhs = "Hillary"), control = list(verbose = F))

inspect(head((sort(tweetsHillary, by = "support", decreasing = T))))
##     lhs          rhs       support confidence lift     count
## [1] {}        => {Hillary} 0.15    0.1500000  1.000000 15   
## [2] {to}      => {Hillary} 0.10    0.2857143  1.904762 10   
## [3] {Crooked} => {Hillary} 0.07    0.8750000  5.833333  7   
## [4] {a}       => {Hillary} 0.06    0.3529412  2.352941  6   
## [5] {the}     => {Hillary} 0.05    0.1612903  1.075269  5   
## [6] {a,to}    => {Hillary} 0.05    0.6250000  4.166667  5

This results indicates, that if in a Tweet there is a word “Crooked”, there is a 87,5% chance of the word “Hillary” being typed as well. From the output, we can study, which other words were associated with the word (item) “Hillary”. We might also sort by confidence, but then we would obtain a lot of words with confidence equal 1, where one word (lhs) appeared only once in the dataset.

Using this approach, we might even create an engine, that would suggest new words for the Tweet. Imagine, that POTUS is typing “Crooked”, our engine, would probably indicate the use of “Hillary”, as the next word, because in the training set, 87,5% of times, those words were corresponding.

Vizualization

itemFrequencyPlot(Tweets_1, topN = 10, type = "relative", main = "Top 10 Words in Trump's Tweets (without stopwords, small sample")

itemFrequencyPlot(Tweets_2, topN = 10, type = "relative", main = "Top 10 Words in Trump's Tweets (with stopwords, big sample")

As it was mentioned previously, the stopwords are important, when one is dealing with NLP, however here - in association rules - we encounter a trade off between the possibility of creating any rules and creating the rules which are insightful. Only with pre-prepared small, homogeneous sample of Tweets, we are able to come up with rules and reasoning about the tweet’s components.

After all, there is a lot of “Hillary”, and “Thank” in the Tweets, as well as verbs using to make people feel united like “We” and “our”. This is also an important step, whether we would like to remove every stopword, or leave some of them in order to keep the broader message.

Now we might want to see lift heatmaps, which would indicate, the words that are together the most of the time and other vizualizations. Firstly, we want to create a bigger set of rules, by lowering the confidence rate.

frequencyRules = ruleInduction(frequencyTweets_2, Tweets_2, confidence = .05)
inspect(frequencyRules)

From the above plots, we can see the corresponding rules explained and highlited by confidence, as well as the graph, where the direction between words (items) is indicated in the rules with support and lift explained as size and color, respectively. We can see that from the sample, the word “Thank” shows big support, which means, that it is written often, and is written usually with the word “you”.

Unfortunately with the smaller sample without stopwords, lowering the confidence did not correspond with more rules, as the confidence of the group of words is really low among the subset.

As we can see, there are endless posibilities of researching this and many more dataset further using ARM. It can be perceived as an introduction to Natural Language Processing, where you can load thousands of texts, and see, which words often correspond with each other. The science of learning about sets can be really intricate but also rewarding!
